/* ============================================================
   Reasoning GP — Audio library scripts (2 of 5)
   CKS-style clinician summaries. Gastrointestinal · Renal & Urology · MSK.
   ~5 min each: definition & lay explanation → risk factors → red flags →
   assessment → non-drug management → drug management → safety-netting →
   referral. Original summaries based on NICE CKS / NG guidance.
   ============================================================ */
window.RGP_AUDIO_TRACKS = (window.RGP_AUDIO_TRACKS || []).concat([

  /* ---------------- GASTROINTESTINAL ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-dyspepsia', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🔥', dur:'5 min', title:'Dyspepsia & GORD', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for dyspepsia and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Definition: dyspepsia is a group of upper abdominal symptoms — pain or discomfort, fullness, early satiety, bloating, and heartburn. Reflux disease is symptoms or mucosal damage caused by acid coming back up from the stomach into the oesophagus. In lay terms, it helps to explain to the patient that the valve at the top of the stomach is letting acid escape upwards, which irritates the gullet and causes the burning they feel; this is very common and usually not serious, but we check carefully to make sure it is not something that needs further tests. Risk factors include increasing age, obesity, smoking, alcohol, a high-fat or spicy diet, caffeine, stress, pregnancy, a hiatus hernia, and certain drugs — NSAIDs, aspirin, calcium-channel blockers, nitrates, and bisphosphonates. Red flags are the priority. Under NICE guideline NG12, refer for an urgent direct-access upper gastrointestinal endoscopy within two weeks for anyone with dysphagia, that is difficulty swallowing, at any age; and for people aged 55 and over with weight loss combined with upper abdominal pain, reflux, or dyspepsia. Other alarm features prompting urgent assessment include gastrointestinal bleeding, an upper abdominal mass, iron-deficiency anaemia, and persistent vomiting. Assessment: take a history of the symptom pattern, drug use especially NSAIDs, smoking, alcohol, and weight, and examine for epigastric tenderness, a mass, and anaemia. Check a full blood count, and test for Helicobacter pylori with a stool antigen or breath test, having stopped any proton-pump inhibitor for two weeks beforehand to avoid a false negative. Non-drug management comes first and should be emphasised: support weight loss if overweight, smoking cessation, and reducing alcohol, caffeine, fizzy drinks, and trigger foods; eating smaller meals and not eating within three to four hours of lying down; raising the head of the bed; and reviewing and stopping where possible drugs that worsen reflux. These measures alone resolve symptoms for many people. Drug management: for uncomplicated dyspepsia, offer either a one-month course of a full-dose proton-pump inhibitor, or test-and-treat for H. pylori. If H. pylori is positive, give eradication therapy — a PPI with two antibiotics for seven days — and confirm eradication where indicated, for example in peptic ulcer disease. For proven reflux disease, offer a full-dose PPI for four to eight weeks, then step down to the lowest effective dose or as-needed use, as long-term acid suppression has risks. Review people on long-term PPIs at least annually and try to reduce or stop. Safety-netting: advise the person to come back promptly if they develop difficulty or pain on swallowing, unintentional weight loss, vomiting, black tarry stools, or if symptoms persist or relapse despite treatment. Refer for endoscopy for any alarm features, treatment-refractory or relapsing reflux, or before considering long-term high-dose therapy.' },

  { id:'cks-coeliac', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🌾', dur:'5 min', title:'Coeliac disease', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for coeliac disease. Definition: an immune-mediated systemic disorder triggered by gluten — a protein in wheat, barley, and rye — in genetically susceptible people, causing inflammation and flattening of the small-bowel lining, which impairs absorption of nutrients. In plain language, explain to the patient that their immune system reacts to gluten and damages the lining of the gut, so they cannot absorb food properly; it is a lifelong condition, but it is managed very effectively by removing gluten from the diet, and doing so protects against long-term complications. Risk factors and associations include a first-degree relative with coeliac disease, type 1 diabetes, autoimmune thyroid disease, Down and Turner syndromes, and other autoimmune conditions. Assessment: the presentation is varied and often subtle — diarrhoea, bloating, abdominal pain, and weight loss, but frequently just unexplained iron, B12, or folate deficiency, fatigue, mouth ulcers, or, in children, faltering growth and delayed puberty. Offer testing to anyone with these features and to the higher-risk groups. A crucial point on investigation: serological testing is only valid if the person is still eating gluten — advise them to eat more than one meal containing gluten every day for at least six weeks before the blood test, otherwise the result can be falsely negative. Test anti-tissue transglutaminase IgA together with total IgA to detect IgA deficiency, which would make that test unreliable. Examine for signs of anaemia and, in children, plot growth. Red flags and safety points: do not let a person start a gluten-free diet before testing or before biopsy, because it invalidates the results; and remember coeliac disease raises the long-term risk of osteoporosis and, rarely, small-bowel lymphoma, which is why diagnosis and dietary adherence matter. Management: if serology is positive, refer to gastroenterology for a confirmatory duodenal biopsy, which remains the diagnostic standard in adults. The cornerstone of treatment is non-drug — a strict, lifelong gluten-free diet with specialist dietitian support, which resolves symptoms and reduces complications; this includes education about hidden sources of gluten, food labelling, and cross-contamination, and signposting to patient organisations such as Coeliac UK. Correct nutritional deficiencies — iron, B12, folate, vitamin D, and calcium. Offer pneumococcal vaccination because of associated hyposplenism. Assess and manage bone health with a DXA scan where indicated. Monitoring: review annually with weight, symptoms, dietary adherence, repeat coeliac antibodies to gauge adherence, and haematinics. Safety-netting and referral: refer back for non-responsive or refractory disease, ongoing symptoms despite a strict gluten-free diet — which may indicate inadvertent gluten intake or an alternative diagnosis — or any new alarm features, and support the person with clear written information.' },

  { id:'cks-ibs', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🌀', dur:'5 min', title:'Irritable bowel syndrome', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for irritable bowel syndrome, or IBS. Definition: a chronic functional bowel disorder characterised by abdominal pain related to defecation, with altered bowel habit, in the absence of structural or biochemical disease. In lay terms, reassure the patient that IBS is a real and common condition where the gut is oversensitive and the muscle activity of the bowel is altered — the bowel itself is not damaged and IBS does not lead to cancer or shorten life — but the symptoms are genuine and can significantly affect quality of life, and there is a lot we can do to help. Risk factors and triggers include a previous episode of gastroenteritis, psychological stress, anxiety and depression, and certain foods. Assessment: consider IBS if there has been abdominal pain or discomfort, bloating, or a change in bowel habit for at least six months. The diagnosis is supported by pain relieved by defecation or associated with a change in stool frequency or form, plus features such as bloating, symptoms worse after eating, and the passage of mucus. Red flags must be excluded, as they point away from IBS: rectal bleeding, unintentional weight loss, a family history of bowel or ovarian cancer, anaemia, an abdominal or rectal mass, and onset of new symptoms in someone over 60 — assess these against NG12 cancer criteria. Investigate to exclude conditions that mimic IBS: full blood count, inflammatory markers such as CRP, coeliac serology, and faecal calprotectin to distinguish IBS from inflammatory bowel disease; in women with relevant symptoms, consider a CA-125 for ovarian cancer. Management: make IBS a positive diagnosis once mimics are excluded, rather than a diagnosis of exclusion alone, and explain the condition clearly, as understanding and reassurance are themselves therapeutic. Non-drug management is central: offer dietary and lifestyle advice — regular meals not skipping or rushing, adequate fluids, limiting caffeine, alcohol, and fizzy drinks, adjusting fibre according to the predominant symptom (reducing insoluble fibre such as bran, and trialling soluble fibre such as ispaghula), and limiting fresh fruit. A trial of a low-FODMAP diet, delivered by a dietitian, helps many people. Encourage physical activity and address stress, and offer psychological therapies such as cognitive behavioural therapy or gut-directed hypnotherapy for persistent symptoms. Drug management targets the predominant symptom: an antispasmodic such as mebeverine for pain and cramping; a laxative such as a macrogol for constipation — but avoid lactulose, which causes bloating; and loperamide for diarrhoea. Consider a low-dose tricyclic antidepressant such as amitriptyline as second-line for pain, or an SSRI. Safety-netting and review: advise the person to return if new red-flag symptoms develop, and review regularly, as IBS is typically relapsing and remitting; refer for diagnostic uncertainty, alarm features, or symptoms refractory to optimal primary-care management.' },

  { id:'cks-constipation', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🚽', dur:'5 min', title:'Constipation in adults', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for constipation in adults. Definition: defecation that is unsatisfactory because of infrequent stools, difficulty passing stool, or a sensation of incomplete emptying. In lay language, explain that the stool is moving too slowly or is too hard, which is extremely common and usually not dangerous, and that simple changes to diet, fluids, and activity, alongside laxatives if needed, almost always sort it out. Risk factors include low dietary fibre, inadequate fluid intake, physical inactivity, older age, pregnancy, ignoring the urge to defecate, and constipating drugs — opioids, iron, some antidepressants, calcium-channel blockers, and antimuscarinics. Assessment: clarify exactly what the person means by constipation, the stool frequency and consistency using the Bristol stool scale, and the duration. Ask about diet, fluids, activity, and medications, and identify secondary causes — hypothyroidism, hypercalcaemia, diabetes, and neurological disease. Red flags must be screened for: a new change in bowel habit in someone aged 50 or over, rectal bleeding, unintentional weight loss, abdominal or rectal mass, or iron-deficiency anaemia, which warrant assessment for colorectal cancer including a FIT test and possible suspected-cancer referral. Examine the abdomen and perform a rectal examination to assess for impaction, masses, and anorectal disease such as fissures. Investigate with blood tests for calcium, thyroid function, and glucose where a secondary cause is suspected, and FIT or referral for red flags. Non-drug management should be tried and emphasised: increase dietary fibre gradually — wholegrains, fruit, and vegetables — increase fluid intake, and encourage regular physical activity; advise responding promptly to the urge to defecate and good toileting posture, such as using a footstool to raise the knees. Drug management follows the laxative ladder: start with a bulk-forming laxative such as ispaghula, ensuring adequate fluids; if stools remain hard, add or switch to an osmotic laxative such as a macrogol; if stools are soft but difficult to pass, add a stimulant laxative such as senna. For opioid-induced constipation, avoid bulk-forming laxatives and use an osmotic plus a stimulant. Treat faecal impaction with high-dose oral macrogols, escalating to suppositories or enemas if needed. Titrate and then taper laxatives once a regular, comfortable pattern is established. Safety-netting and referral: advise return if symptoms persist despite treatment, or if any red-flag features develop. Refer for suspected malignancy under NG12, suspected secondary causes, impaction unresponsive to treatment, or chronic constipation refractory to optimal management.' },

  { id:'cks-rectal-bleeding', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🩸', dur:'5 min', title:'Rectal bleeding & colorectal cancer', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for rectal bleeding and suspected colorectal cancer, guided by NICE NG12. In lay terms, it is worth telling the patient that most rectal bleeding comes from harmless causes such as piles or a small tear, but because bleeding can occasionally be the first sign of bowel cancer, we use a simple stool test and, where needed, a camera test to be sure — and that finding any problem early gives the best outcome. Risk factors for colorectal cancer include increasing age, a family history of bowel or ovarian cancer, inflammatory bowel disease, previous polyps, and lifestyle factors such as obesity, smoking, alcohol, processed and red meat, and inactivity. Assessment: take a history of the bleeding — its colour, whether it is on the paper, coats the stool, or is mixed in — and associated change in bowel habit, abdominal pain, weight loss, and family history. Bright-red blood on wiping or on the surface of stool more often suggests an anorectal cause, whereas darker blood mixed through the stool is more concerning, but appearance alone cannot exclude cancer. Examine the abdomen for a mass and perform a rectal examination. Red flags and referral thresholds: the faecal immunochemical test, FIT, now guides urgent referral — offer FIT to people with symptoms, and refer on a suspected-cancer pathway for an appointment within two weeks if FIT is positive at 10 micrograms of haemoglobin per gram or more. Also refer urgently for an unexplained abdominal or rectal mass, or an unexplained anal mass or ulceration, regardless of FIT. Check a full blood count, because unexplained iron-deficiency anaemia itself prompts investigation for gastrointestinal malignancy. Management: refer according to the FIT result and red flags. Treat clearly benign causes such as haemorrhoids or an anal fissure with non-drug measures first — increasing dietary fibre and fluids to soften the stool and avoid straining — alongside topical treatments where appropriate; but remember benign anorectal disease and cancer can coexist, so investigate if there is any doubt or persistence. Be aware the national bowel-cancer screening programme runs separately by age and does not replace symptomatic assessment — a person within the screening programme who develops symptoms still needs assessing. Safety-netting is essential: advise the person clearly to return if bleeding persists or recurs, the bowel habit changes, or other symptoms such as weight loss develop, and re-refer if symptoms continue despite an initially negative assessment. The key teaching point is that visible rectal bleeding with relevant features should never simply be attributed to piles without appropriate assessment and safety-netting.' },

  { id:'cks-gallstones', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🟡', dur:'5 min', title:'Gallstones', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for gallstones. Definition: stones that form in the gallbladder or biliary tree, which are common and frequently asymptomatic, but can cause biliary colic and serious complications. In plain language, explain that the gallbladder stores bile to help digest fat, and stones can form in it like little pebbles; many cause no trouble at all, but if one blocks the outflow it causes pain, and occasionally a stone can cause infection or inflammation that needs urgent treatment. Risk factors are classically summarised as the "five Fs" — female, fertile, forty, fat, and family history — alongside rapid weight loss, diabetes, and certain drugs. Assessment: biliary colic presents as severe, constant pain in the right upper quadrant or epigastrium, often after a fatty meal, radiating to the back or right shoulder blade, lasting from minutes to a few hours then settling, with nausea. Ask about and examine for features of complications. Red flags requiring urgent action: persistent pain with fever suggests acute cholecystitis; jaundice with pale stools and dark urine suggests a stone obstructing the bile duct; and the triad of pain, fever, and jaundice suggests ascending cholangitis, a medical emergency. Severe epigastric pain radiating to the back with vomiting raises gallstone pancreatitis. Investigate with liver function tests and inflammatory markers, and arrange an abdominal ultrasound of the gallbladder and biliary tree as first-line imaging. Management: for asymptomatic gallstones found incidentally within the gallbladder, no treatment is usually needed, and you can reassure the patient. Non-drug advice for symptomatic stones includes eating a lower-fat diet to reduce attacks while awaiting treatment, and weight management. For symptomatic biliary colic, manage pain with analgesia such as an NSAID or, for severe pain, an opioid, with an antiemetic, and refer for consideration of laparoscopic cholecystectomy — removal of the gallbladder — which is the definitive treatment for symptomatic disease and is offered electively. Safety-netting and urgent referral: advise the person to seek urgent help for fever, persistent or worsening pain lasting more than a few hours, or jaundice. Refer or admit urgently for acute cholecystitis, which needs same-day assessment; ascending cholangitis and gallstone pancreatitis, which are emergencies; and arrange removal of common bile-duct stones, usually by ERCP. Provide interim safety-netting and follow-up while the person awaits elective surgery.' },

  { id:'cks-ida', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🩸', dur:'5 min', title:'Iron deficiency anaemia', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for iron deficiency anaemia. Definition: anaemia caused by insufficient iron to make red blood cells, producing a microcytic, hypochromic anaemia — small, pale cells. In lay language, explain that the blood is low because the body lacks iron, the building block for the red pigment that carries oxygen; the important part is not just to top up the iron but to work out why it became low in the first place. Causes and risk factors: blood loss is the commonest mechanism — heavy menstrual periods in younger women, and gastrointestinal blood loss at any age; malabsorption such as coeliac disease; increased demand in pregnancy and growth; and dietary insufficiency, particularly in vegetarian or restricted diets and older people. Assessment: ask about symptoms of anaemia — fatigue, breathlessness, palpitations, and reduced exercise tolerance — about menstrual and gastrointestinal blood loss, diet, and features of malabsorption, and screen for gastrointestinal red flags such as change in bowel habit, weight loss, and abdominal pain. Examine for pallor, koilonychia, glossitis, and signs of a cause. Confirm with a full blood count showing low haemoglobin and a low mean cell volume, and a low ferritin, which is the most useful single test — though ferritin is an acute-phase protein and can be falsely normal or raised in inflammation, so interpret alongside CRP. Red flags and referral: in men of any age and in postmenopausal women, unexplained iron-deficiency anaemia must be investigated with upper and lower gastrointestinal endoscopy under NG12, because it can be the first sign of gastrointestinal cancer. Always test for coeliac disease. In premenopausal women, menstrual loss is the usual cause, but still consider gastrointestinal investigation if there are symptoms or it is otherwise unexplained. Management: treat with oral iron such as ferrous sulfate or ferrous fumarate, given once daily or, to improve absorption and reduce side effects, on alternate days; continue for around three months after the haemoglobin normalises to replenish stores. Advise taking it with vitamin C-containing drinks and managing common side effects such as constipation and dark stools. Non-drug and underlying-cause management is essential: treat the source — for example manage menorrhagia, treat coeliac disease, or address dietary inadequacy — and give dietary advice on iron-rich foods. Recheck the full blood count to confirm response. Safety-netting and referral: refer for failure to respond to oral iron despite adherence, intolerance needing intravenous iron, ongoing or brisk blood loss, or where investigation of the cause is indicated; and advise return for new gastrointestinal symptoms.' },

  { id:'cks-haemorrhoids', cat:'Gastrointestinal', ic:'🩹', dur:'5 min', title:'Haemorrhoids', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for haemorrhoids. Definition: symptomatic enlargement and downward displacement of the normal anal cushions — spongy vascular tissue in the anal canal — classified as internal or external, with internal ones graded one to four by the degree of prolapse. In plain language, reassure the patient that piles are swollen blood vessels in the back passage, are extremely common, and are not dangerous, but it is important not to assume all rectal bleeding is just piles, so we check carefully. Risk factors include constipation and straining, a low-fibre diet, pregnancy, ageing, prolonged sitting, and raised intra-abdominal pressure. Assessment: typical symptoms are bright-red rectal bleeding on the surface of the stool or on wiping, anal itching, discomfort, a feeling of incomplete emptying, and a prolapsing lump. Ask about bowel habit, straining, and constipation. Red flags: do not assume haemorrhoids if there is a change in bowel habit, darker blood mixed with the stool, weight loss, or anaemia — these need assessment for colorectal cancer under NG12 with FIT. Examine the perianal area and perform a rectal examination; internal haemorrhoids are often not palpable, so proctoscopy helps to visualise them. Check a full blood count if bleeding is significant, and use FIT and consider referral if there is any diagnostic uncertainty or red flags. Non-drug management is first-line and emphasised: increase dietary fibre and fluids to soften the stool and avoid straining, offering a bulk-forming laxative if needed; advise good anal hygiene, avoiding excessive wiping, and not delaying or straining at defecation. These measures resolve most early symptoms. Drug management: short-term topical preparations, some containing a corticosteroid or local anaesthetic, may ease symptoms but should not be used for more than about a week because of skin effects. For persistent or higher-grade symptomatic haemorrhoids not responding to conservative measures, refer for outpatient procedures such as rubber-band ligation, or for surgery for large or refractory disease. Recognise a thrombosed external haemorrhoid — an acutely painful, tense perianal lump — and manage with analgesia, ice, and conservative measures, referring early if the person presents within the first day or two, when surgical evacuation may help. Safety-netting: advise return for ongoing or heavier bleeding, a change in bowel habit, or new symptoms, and re-evaluate or refer if bleeding continues despite treatment of presumed haemorrhoids.' },

  /* ---------------- RENAL & UROLOGY ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-ckd', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'🫘', dur:'5 min', title:'Chronic kidney disease', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for chronic kidney disease, or CKD, following NICE guideline NG203. Definition: abnormalities of kidney structure or function present for more than three months, classified by the eGFR category, G1 to G5, and the albuminuria category, A1 to A3, based on the urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio, the ACR. In lay terms, explain that the kidneys filter waste from the blood, and in CKD they are not filtering quite as well as they should; most people with early CKD never develop serious problems, and the aim of treatment is to protect the kidneys and the heart and to stop it progressing. Risk factors include diabetes, hypertension, cardiovascular disease, recurrent urinary infections or obstruction, nephrotoxic drugs, increasing age, and a family history of kidney disease. Assessment: CKD is usually detected on routine testing rather than symptoms. Confirm the diagnosis with eGFR and ACR sustained over at least three months, and dipstick the urine for blood. The ACR strongly drives both risk and treatment, so quantify albuminuria with an early-morning sample. Image with ultrasound where obstruction, progressive disease, haematuria, or a structural or genetic cause is suspected. Red flags and referral: refer to nephrology for an eGFR below 30, an ACR of 70 or more, a sustained rapid decline in eGFR, refractory hyperkalaemia or hypertension, suspected genetic or treatable disease, or unexplained haematuria with proteinuria. Non-drug management underpins everything: support smoking cessation, weight management, regular exercise, a reduced-salt diet, and review of nephrotoxic over-the-counter drugs such as NSAIDs. Crucially, give sick-day rule advice — to temporarily stop certain medicines, including ACE inhibitors, ARBs, diuretics, and SGLT2 inhibitors, during acute dehydrating illness such as vomiting or diarrhoea, to protect the kidneys. Drug management aims to slow progression and reduce cardiovascular risk: optimise blood pressure, and offer an ACE inhibitor or ARB to people with diabetes and an ACR of 3 or more, hypertension with an ACR of 30 or more, or anyone with an ACR of 70 or more, checking renal function and potassium one to two weeks after starting and accepting a stable fall in eGFR of up to 25 percent. Offer an SGLT2 inhibitor such as dapagliflozin to those meeting the ACR and eGFR criteria, as it slows progression and protects the heart. Offer atorvastatin 20 milligrams for cardiovascular prevention, and treat complications such as anaemia and renal bone disease. Monitoring and safety-netting: review eGFR and ACR at a frequency matched to the stage and risk, and advise the person on the sick-day rules and on seeking review during significant illness.' },

  { id:'cks-aki', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'🫘', dur:'5 min', title:'Acute kidney injury', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for acute kidney injury, or AKI. Definition: an abrupt decline in kidney function over hours to days, detected by a rise in serum creatinine or a fall in urine output, and staged 1 to 3 by severity. In lay language, explain that the kidneys have suddenly slowed down, usually because of dehydration, infection, or a medicine, and that in most cases, if we find and fix the cause quickly, the kidneys recover. Causes are grouped into three: pre-renal, from reduced blood flow to the kidneys due to dehydration, vomiting, diarrhoea, sepsis, or heart failure; intrinsic renal, from damage within the kidney by drugs, glomerular disease, or interstitial nephritis; and post-renal, from obstruction such as an enlarged prostate, stones, or a pelvic tumour. Risk factors include older age, pre-existing chronic kidney disease, diabetes, heart failure, and nephrotoxic drugs. Assessment: identify the people at risk and the precipitant. Ask about reduced fluid intake or output, the acute illness, and nephrotoxic medicines. Examine fluid status carefully — pulse, blood pressure, capillary refill, and JVP — and palpate for a distended bladder suggesting obstruction. Investigate with urea and electrolytes to stage the injury, a urine dipstick, and an ultrasound if obstruction is suspected. Red flags: check potassium urgently, as hyperkalaemia is the dangerous immediate complication and can cause fatal arrhythmia; and watch for features of sepsis, fluid overload, or a positive dipstick for blood and protein suggesting intrinsic renal disease. Management: treat the cause. Rehydrate with appropriate fluids in pre-renal injury, relieve obstruction with catheterisation or urgent urology referral, and treat sepsis. Non-drug and medicines management is central: stop nephrotoxic and contributing drugs — the sick-day drugs such as ACE inhibitors, ARBs, diuretics, NSAIDs, and metformin — and review the whole medication list, adjusting renally-cleared drugs. Monitor renal function, fluid balance, and potassium closely, and treat hyperkalaemia promptly. Restart appropriate medicines once recovered. Safety-netting and referral: admit or seek urgent specialist advice for stage 3 injury, dangerous biochemistry such as hyperkalaemia, fluid overload, suspected intrinsic renal disease, obstruction needing intervention, or no clear reversible cause. After recovery, monitor renal function, because an episode of AKI increases the future risk of chronic kidney disease, and educate the person about the sick-day rules to prevent recurrence.' },

  { id:'cks-uti', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'💧', dur:'5 min', title:'Urinary tract infection', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for lower urinary tract infection in adults. Definition: infection of the bladder and urethra, presenting with dysuria, frequency, urgency, suprapubic pain, and cloudy or offensive urine; UTI in men and recurrent UTI are considered complicated. In lay terms, explain that bacteria have got into the bladder and are causing irritation, that simple bladder infections are common and usually settle quickly, and that drinking plenty of fluids and, where needed, a short antibiotic course will treat it. Risk factors include female sex, sexual activity, pregnancy, postmenopausal oestrogen deficiency, urinary catheters, diabetes, urinary obstruction or stones, and immunosuppression. Assessment: in non-pregnant women under 65 with clear urinary symptoms, the diagnosis can be made clinically. A urine dipstick can support the diagnosis in milder or equivocal cases — nitrites or leucocytes with red cells raise the probability — but in adults over 65 dipsticks are unreliable, and asymptomatic bacteriuria should not be treated. Send a urine culture in pregnancy, in men, and in treatment failure, recurrent infection, suspected pyelonephritis, or atypical features. Red flags: distinguish upper UTI, or pyelonephritis, with fever, loin pain, and systemic illness, and recognise sepsis, which needs urgent assessment. In frail older people, beware attributing non-specific decline to a UTI in the absence of urinary symptoms — over-diagnosis is common and harmful. Non-drug management: encourage adequate fluid intake and analgesia such as paracetamol; for mild symptoms in otherwise well women, consider a back-up or delayed antibiotic prescription with self-care, as some cases resolve without antibiotics. Drug management follows local antibiotic guidance and stewardship: for uncomplicated cystitis in women, nitrofurantoin is commonly first-line if renal function allows, typically for three days; treat UTI in men for seven days; treat pyelonephritis with an appropriate longer course and consider admission if systemically unwell; and in pregnancy always culture and treat, including asymptomatic bacteriuria, with a pregnancy-safe antibiotic. For recurrent UTI, address risk factors, consider vaginal oestrogen in postmenopausal women, self-care measures, and consider prophylaxis. Safety-netting and referral: advise the person to seek urgent review if they develop fever, loin pain, rigors, vomiting, or feel systemically unwell, as this suggests progression. Refer or admit for sepsis, pyelonephritis not responding, obstruction, or recurrent infection needing investigation.' },

  { id:'cks-haematuria', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'🩸', dur:'5 min', title:'Haematuria', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for haematuria and suspected urological cancer, guided by NICE NG12. Definition: blood in the urine, either visible to the eye, or non-visible, detected on dipstick and confirmed on testing. In plain language, explain to the patient that blood in the urine often has a harmless cause such as an infection, but because it can sometimes be a sign of a problem in the kidney, bladder, or prostate, we arrange tests to be sure, and finding any issue early is important. Risk factors for urothelial cancer include increasing age, smoking — the single biggest modifiable risk — and occupational exposure to certain dyes and chemicals. Assessment: distinguish visible from non-visible haematuria, and ask about urinary symptoms, pain, and risk factors. Importantly, do not assume that anticoagulation, a recent infection, or exercise explains the haematuria — these need the bleeding to be confirmed as resolved and may still warrant investigation. Examine, including blood pressure and an abdominal and, in men, a prostate examination. Red flags and referral thresholds: refer on a suspected-cancer pathway for an appointment within two weeks anyone aged 45 and over with unexplained visible haematuria without urinary infection, or with visible haematuria that persists or recurs after successful treatment of a urinary infection; and refer people aged 60 and over with unexplained non-visible haematuria together with either dysuria or a raised white-cell count. Investigate to assess for a renal cause: confirm with a urine culture to exclude infection, check renal function, and measure the ACR, because haematuria with significant proteinuria suggests intrinsic kidney disease needing nephrology rather than urology. Management: refer according to the thresholds for cystoscopy and upper-tract imaging. Treat a urinary infection where found and recheck the urine after treatment to confirm the blood has cleared. For non-visible haematuria with a renal cause — significant proteinuria, a declining eGFR, or hypertension — refer to nephrology. Non-drug advice includes smoking cessation, given the link with bladder cancer. Safety-netting: explain that most causes turn out not to be cancer, but that prompt investigation is to exclude serious disease; advise the person to return and be re-referred if visible haematuria recurs after an initially negative assessment, and ensure clear follow-up of all results.' },

  { id:'cks-luts-men', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'🚹', dur:'5 min', title:'LUTS in men', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for lower urinary tract symptoms in men, commonly arising from benign prostatic enlargement. In lay terms, explain that the prostate gland sits around the water pipe and tends to enlarge with age, which can squeeze the pipe and change the way the bladder empties; this is very common, usually not due to cancer, and there are effective treatments. Risk factors include increasing age, family history, and obesity. Assessment: separate voiding symptoms — hesitancy, a weak or intermittent stream, straining, terminal dribbling, and a feeling of incomplete emptying — from storage symptoms — frequency, urgency, nocturia, and urgency incontinence. Quantify the impact using the International Prostate Symptom Score and a frequency-volume chart. Examine the abdomen for a palpable bladder and perform a digital rectal examination to assess prostate size and texture. Red flags: ask about visible haematuria, pain, and features suggesting prostate cancer such as a hard or irregular prostate, bone pain, or weight loss; recognise acute urinary retention — a painful, palpable bladder unable to void — as an emergency, and chronic retention with overflow. Investigate with a urine dipstick, renal function, and, after counselling on the benefits and limitations, a PSA test, particularly with voiding symptoms, an abnormal prostate, or cancer concern. Non-drug management first: offer reassurance and conservative measures for mild or non-bothersome symptoms — fluid advice, reducing caffeine and alcohol especially in the evening, bladder training, double voiding, and reviewing diuretics and their timing. Drug management: for bothersome voiding symptoms with prostatic enlargement, start an alpha-blocker such as tamsulosin for relatively rapid relief; for a significantly enlarged prostate, add or use a 5-alpha-reductase inhibitor such as finasteride, which shrinks the prostate over several months and reduces the risk of progression and retention. For predominant storage symptoms or overactive bladder, offer an antimuscarinic or mirabegron alongside bladder training; combination therapy suits men with both bothersome storage and voiding symptoms. Safety-netting and referral: advise the person to seek urgent help if unable to pass urine. Refer for suspected prostate or bladder cancer, acute or chronic retention, recurrent infection, bladder stones, renal impairment from obstruction, or symptoms not controlled by treatment. Review symptom scores and treatment response, and reassess PSA and the prostate as appropriate.' },

  { id:'cks-renal-colic', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'🪨', dur:'5 min', title:'Renal & ureteric colic', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for renal and ureteric colic from urinary stones. Definition: acute pain caused by a stone obstructing the urinary tract. In plain language, explain that a small stone has formed in the kidney and is now trying to pass down the narrow tube to the bladder, which causes intense waves of pain; most small stones pass on their own with pain relief, fluids, and time. Risk factors include dehydration, a personal or family history of stones, a high-protein or high-salt diet, obesity, and certain metabolic conditions and drugs. Assessment: the classic presentation is sudden, severe, colicky loin pain radiating to the groin, with the person restless and unable to find a comfortable position — in contrast to peritonitis, where people lie still — often with nausea, vomiting, and visible or non-visible haematuria. Examine for loin tenderness and check observations. Red flags: ask about fever, because a stone obstructing the kidney with infection above it is a urological emergency requiring urgent drainage; and watch for acute kidney injury, a single or transplanted kidney, and pregnancy. Investigate with a urine dipstick for blood, renal function, and serum calcium and urate. The first-line imaging is a low-dose non-contrast CT of the kidneys, ureters, and bladder, arranged urgently — within 24 hours of presentation. Management: provide effective analgesia promptly — an NSAID such as diclofenac is first-line, given rectally or intramuscularly if needed, with an opioid as an alternative, plus an antiemetic. Many stones, particularly small distal ureteric stones under 5 millimetres, pass spontaneously, and medical expulsive therapy with an alpha-blocker such as tamsulosin may aid passage of distal ureteric stones. Non-drug advice: encourage fluid intake and ask the person to strain their urine to catch the stone for analysis. Safety-netting and referral: refer urgently or admit for any features of infection with obstruction, which needs emergency drainage; acute kidney injury; a single or transplanted kidney; uncontrolled pain or persistent vomiting; or pregnancy. Refer to urology for stones unlikely to pass, larger stones, or those needing intervention such as lithotripsy or ureteroscopy. After an episode, assess for metabolic risk factors and advise on prevention — high fluid intake aiming for pale urine, and reducing dietary salt and excess animal protein — to reduce the high recurrence rate.' },

  { id:'cks-ed', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'💙', dur:'5 min', title:'Erectile dysfunction', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for erectile dysfunction. Definition: the persistent inability to achieve or maintain an erection sufficient for satisfactory sexual performance. A crucial teaching point is that erectile dysfunction is commonly vascular and is an important early warning sign of cardiovascular disease, sometimes preceding a heart attack by years. In lay terms, sensitively explain that erections depend on healthy blood flow, so problems can be an early signal that the blood vessels need attention, and that this is common, treatable, and worth addressing both for the symptom and for overall health. Risk factors include increasing age, diabetes, hypertension, high cholesterol, smoking, obesity, physical inactivity, excess alcohol, depression and anxiety, relationship difficulties, and many drugs. Assessment: clarify the onset, whether it is situational, and the presence of spontaneous morning erections, which point towards a psychological component. Ask about cardiovascular risk factors, diabetes, medications, smoking, alcohol, mood, and relationship factors. Examine — blood pressure, BMI, peripheral pulses, and a genital examination — and consider the prostate. Investigate with HbA1c, a lipid profile, and a morning testosterone, adding thyroid function and prolactin if testosterone is low; calculate cardiovascular risk and treat the presentation as a prompt for full vascular risk assessment. Non-drug management is foundational and should be emphasised: address modifiable factors — weight loss, regular exercise, stopping smoking, and reducing alcohol — which can themselves improve erections and cardiovascular health; review and where possible change causative drugs; and offer psychosexual counselling where psychological factors predominate, ideally involving the partner. Drug management: first-line is a phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitor such as sildenafil or tadalafil, taken correctly with sexual stimulation, and absolutely contraindicated with nitrates because of dangerous hypotension; counsel on correct use and trial several doses before judging effectiveness. Treat confirmed low testosterone, usually after specialist advice. Safety-netting and referral: actively manage cardiovascular risk. Refer to urology or specialist services for younger men, those not responding to oral treatment who may benefit from intracavernosal injections, vacuum devices, or surgery, and for endocrine causes such as significant hypogonadism or hyperprolactinaemia. Review the response to treatment and cardiovascular risk-factor management over time, and address the impact on the person and their relationship.' },

  { id:'cks-hyperkalaemia', cat:'Renal & Urology', ic:'⚡', dur:'5 min', title:'Hyperkalaemia', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for hyperkalaemia. Definition: a serum potassium above the normal range, graded as mild around 5.5 to 5.9, moderate 6.0 to 6.4, and severe 6.5 millimoles per litre or above; it matters because a high potassium can cause life-threatening cardiac arrhythmia. In lay terms, explain that potassium is a salt the body needs in careful balance, and too much can affect the heart rhythm, which is why we check the heart and act quickly when it is high. Causes and risk factors include chronic kidney disease and acute kidney injury, drugs such as ACE inhibitors, ARBs, mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists like spironolactone, and potassium supplements, Addison\u2019s disease, and excessive dietary intake, often in combination. Assessment: hyperkalaemia is frequently found on routine bloods and may be asymptomatic, or cause muscle weakness, fatigue, or palpitations. The first step is to exclude a spurious result — pseudohyperkalaemia from haemolysis, a difficult or delayed sample, or a high platelet count — by repeating the test urgently. Then assess the cause by reviewing renal function and the full medication list, and the clinical context, including any acute illness causing AKI. Red flags: the crucial investigation is an ECG to look for signs of cardiac toxicity — tall, peaked T waves, flattened or absent P waves, and a widened QRS complex — and any of these, or a potassium of 6.5 or above, is a medical emergency. Management is directed by severity. A potassium of 6.5 or above, or any ECG changes, needs immediate hospital treatment with intravenous calcium gluconate to stabilise the heart, and insulin with dextrose to drive potassium into the cells. For moderate hyperkalaemia, seek urgent advice and arrange assessment. For mild, stable hyperkalaemia without ECG changes, identify and treat the cause: stop or reduce contributing drugs, treat the underlying condition, and give dietary potassium advice — reducing high-potassium foods such as bananas, potatoes, and salt substitutes. Non-drug and medicines management: always confirm a genuine result before acting, and after an episode review medicines that raise potassium, especially in chronic kidney disease, and monitor potassium after starting or up-titrating renin-angiotensin drugs. Safety-netting: arrange appropriate recheck intervals, and ensure the person and the team know to act on a high result promptly given the arrhythmia risk.' },

  /* ---------------- MUSCULOSKELETAL ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-back-pain', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'🧍', dur:'5 min', title:'Low back pain & sciatica', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for low back pain and sciatica, following NICE guideline NG59. Definition: most low back pain is non-specific, without a serious or identifiable underlying cause; sciatica is radicular leg pain arising from nerve-root involvement. In lay language, reassure the patient that most back pain is not due to any serious damage, that scans often show wear-and-tear changes that are normal for age and do not explain the pain, and that staying active and keeping moving is the single most helpful thing for recovery — resting in bed actually slows healing. Risk factors include heavy or repetitive lifting, sedentary work, obesity, low mood, and previous episodes. Assessment: take a history of the pain, leg symptoms, and function. The priority is to screen for red flags. Cauda equina syndrome — bilateral leg pain, saddle or perineal numbness, bladder or bowel dysfunction such as retention or incontinence, and sexual dysfunction — is a surgical emergency needing immediate referral for MRI. Other red flags suggest malignancy, such as a history of cancer, weight loss, and night pain; infection, such as fever and immunosuppression; fracture, such as significant trauma or osteoporosis; and inflammatory back pain such as ankylosing spondylitis — insidious onset under the age of 40, prolonged morning stiffness, and improvement with exercise rather than rest. Examine spinal movement, perform a lower-limb neurological examination and straight-leg raise, and assess saddle sensation and anal tone if cauda equina is suspected. Imaging is not indicated for non-specific back pain; arrange urgent imaging and referral for red flags, and consider a risk-stratification tool such as STarT Back to match support to risk. Non-drug management is the foundation: give reassurance and information, encourage continuing normal activities and work, and offer a structured exercise programme; consider manual therapy or a psychologically-informed programme within a package of care, and address fears about movement. Drug management: offer an oral NSAID at the lowest effective dose for the shortest time, with gastroprotection where needed; avoid paracetamol alone, and avoid opioids where possible, particularly long-term. For sciatica, take the same active approach, consider a neuropathic agent only if indicated, and refer for persistent or severe radicular pain for imaging and specialist treatment. Safety-netting and referral: refer immediately for suspected cauda equina, and per NG12 or relevant pathways for suspected serious pathology; advise the person which symptoms — especially bladder, bowel, or saddle changes — require emergency attention, and review progress and support return to normal function.' },

  { id:'cks-oa', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'🦵', dur:'5 min', title:'Osteoarthritis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for osteoarthritis, following NICE guideline NG226. Definition: a common condition of joint pain and stiffness caused by cartilage loss and bone remodelling, commonly affecting the knees, hips, hands, and spine. In lay terms, it is helpful to move away from calling it simply "wear and tear", which sounds hopeless; explain instead that it is an active process the joint goes through, that the amount of change on an x-ray often does not match how much pain someone has, and that staying active and strengthening the muscles around the joint genuinely reduces pain and improves function. Risk factors include increasing age, obesity, female sex, previous joint injury or surgery, occupational or sporting overload, and genetic factors. Assessment: a key point is that osteoarthritis can be diagnosed clinically, without imaging, in a person aged 45 or over who has activity-related joint pain and either no morning stiffness or morning stiffness lasting no longer than 30 minutes. Ask about pain that worsens with use and eases with rest, functional limitation, and the impact on daily life, sleep, and mood. Examine for bony swelling, crepitus, reduced range of movement, and the absence of features suggesting inflammatory arthritis or infection. Red flags: consider alternative or additional diagnoses if there is a hot, swollen joint suggesting infection or crystal arthritis, marked rest or night pain, rapid deterioration, or systemic features. X-rays are not needed to confirm the diagnosis and correlate poorly with symptoms; investigate only to exclude other conditions. Non-drug management is the cornerstone and should be offered to everyone: therapeutic exercise — both muscle strengthening and aerobic — improves pain and function and is core treatment; weight loss for those overweight meaningfully reduces symptoms, particularly in the knee and hip; and provide information, support self-management, and consider walking aids, appropriate footwear, and workplace adjustments. Drug management is adjunctive: offer a topical NSAID first-line for knee osteoarthritis; then consider an oral NSAID at the lowest effective dose for the shortest time with gastroprotection, weighing cardiovascular, renal, and gastrointestinal risks; topical capsaicin is an option. Do not routinely offer paracetamol alone or weak opioids, given limited benefit and risk of harm. Consider an intra-articular corticosteroid injection for short-term relief of moderate to severe pain. Safety-netting and referral: refer for consideration of joint replacement when symptoms substantially affect quality of life and are refractory to non-surgical management, and do not let age, weight, or x-ray appearance alone be a barrier to referral; review the impact and treatment response over time.' },

  { id:'cks-gout', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'🦶', dur:'5 min', title:'Gout', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for gout. Definition: a crystal arthropathy caused by deposition of monosodium urate crystals in and around joints, related to a raised blood uric acid level. In lay language, explain that uric acid is a waste product that, when it builds up, can form tiny sharp crystals in the joint, triggering sudden intense inflammation; it is very treatable, both to settle an attack and, with a daily tablet, to prevent future attacks by lowering the uric acid. Risk factors include male sex, increasing age, obesity, a diet high in red meat, seafood, and sugary drinks, excess alcohol especially beer, diuretics, chronic kidney disease, and a family history. Assessment: the classic acute attack is a rapid onset, over hours, of an intensely painful, hot, red, swollen joint, often the first metatarsophalangeal joint at the base of the big toe. Ask about previous attacks, diet, alcohol, diuretics, and renal disease, and examine the affected joint and look for tophi — urate deposits — in chronic disease. Red flags: the crucial differential is septic arthritis, which can look identical; if there is any doubt, especially with fever or systemic illness, treat as septic arthritis until proven otherwise and arrange urgent joint aspiration. Measure serum urate to support the diagnosis, but note it can be normal during an acute attack, so recheck a few weeks later; check renal function and cardiovascular risk factors. Drug management of the acute flare: start treatment as early as possible — first-line is an NSAID with gastroprotection, or colchicine at a low dose of 500 micrograms two to four times daily to limit diarrhoea, or a short course of an oral corticosteroid if those are unsuitable. Rest, elevate, and ice the joint, and continue any existing urate-lowering therapy through the attack. Long-term management: offer urate-lowering therapy to people with recurrent flares, tophi, joint damage, or chronic kidney disease, and discuss it with everyone after a first attack. First-line is allopurinol, started at a low dose and titrated up, aiming for a serum urate below 300 micromoles per litre. Co-prescribe colchicine or an NSAID as prophylaxis when starting, continuing for up to six months, to prevent the flares that titration can trigger; do not stop urate-lowering therapy during an acute attack. Non-drug management: address lifestyle — weight loss, reducing alcohol and purine-rich foods and sugary drinks — and review medications such as diuretics. Safety-netting and referral: advise prompt treatment of flares and explain the preventive aim of long-term therapy; refer for diagnostic uncertainty, treatment failure, intolerance of urate-lowering drugs, or complicated disease.' },

  { id:'cks-ra', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'🤲', dur:'5 min', title:'Rheumatoid arthritis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for rheumatoid arthritis. Definition: a chronic systemic autoimmune inflammatory arthritis, typically a symmetrical polyarthritis affecting the small joints of the hands and feet, which without treatment causes progressive joint damage and disability. In lay terms, explain that the immune system is mistakenly attacking the lining of the joints, causing inflammation, pain, and swelling, and that the key message is that early treatment can control the disease and prevent permanent joint damage — so getting seen by a specialist quickly really matters. Risk factors include female sex, a family history, smoking, and increasing age into middle life. Assessment: ask about joint pain and swelling, prolonged early-morning stiffness lasting over 30 minutes to an hour, and fatigue. The symmetrical small-joint pattern and the prolonged morning stiffness distinguish it from osteoarthritis, where stiffness is brief. Examine for soft, warm, swollen joints, particularly the metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints and the wrists, and later for characteristic deformities and extra-articular features such as nodules. Investigate with rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies, inflammatory markers, a full blood count, and X-rays of the hands and feet, though early radiographs may be normal. Red flags and the key principle — urgency: refer any adult with suspected persistent synovitis of undetermined cause to rheumatology without delay, and refer urgently if the small joints of the hands or feet are involved, more than one joint is affected, or there has been a delay of three months or more between symptom onset and seeking help. Critically, do not let a normal rheumatoid factor or a normal acute-phase response delay referral, because there is a window of opportunity in which early disease-modifying treatment protects the joints. Management: rheumatoid arthritis is managed by specialists using disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs such as methotrexate, treating to a target of low disease activity or remission. Primary care has important roles: supporting shared-care monitoring of these drugs and their blood tests, recognising and managing flares, addressing the increased cardiovascular risk, ensuring vaccinations, managing the increased infection risk, and supporting the person. Non-drug support includes physiotherapy and occupational therapy, exercise, smoking cessation, and patient education. Safety-netting and referral: refer flares and complications promptly, seek advice for intercurrent illness in someone on immunosuppression, and review wellbeing, function, mood, and comorbidity at regular intervals.' },

  { id:'cks-pmr', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'🧓', dur:'5 min', title:'Polymyalgia rheumatica', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for polymyalgia rheumatica, or PMR. Definition: an inflammatory condition of older adults causing pain and stiffness in the shoulder and pelvic girdles. In lay terms, explain that this is an inflammatory condition causing stiffness and aching around the shoulders and hips, that it typically responds dramatically to a steroid tablet — often within days — and that treatment usually continues for a year or two while we gradually reduce the dose. Risk factors: it almost exclusively affects people over 50, usually over 60, and is more common in women and in people of northern European descent. Assessment: the presentation is a relatively rapid onset of bilateral shoulder and hip-girdle pain and prolonged early-morning stiffness lasting over 45 minutes, making it hard to rise from a chair, turn in bed, or raise the arms to dress. Crucially, always ask about and look for symptoms of giant cell arteritis — a new headache, scalp tenderness, jaw claudication on chewing, and visual disturbance — because this associated condition is an emergency requiring immediate high-dose steroids to prevent irreversible blindness. Examine for painful restriction of active shoulder and hip movement without true muscle weakness, and assess the temporal arteries. Investigate with inflammatory markers, ESR and CRP, which are usually raised, a full blood count, and tests to exclude conditions that mimic PMR — thyroid function, calcium, creatine kinase to exclude a myositis, and protein electrophoresis where myeloma is a concern; a normal inflammatory response makes the diagnosis less likely but does not exclude it. Red flags: any features of giant cell arteritis need same-day assessment and steroids. Drug management: start oral prednisolone, typically around 15 milligrams daily, and a rapid, dramatic response within about a week strongly supports the diagnosis; if there is no good response, reconsider the diagnosis. Reduce the dose gradually over one to two years, guided by symptoms and inflammatory markers, warning the person that relapses are common during reduction. Non-drug and supportive management: because of prolonged steroid use, provide bone protection with a bisphosphonate, gastric protection, a steroid card, and clear sick-day advice not to stop steroids abruptly; give lifestyle advice on bone and cardiovascular health. Safety-netting and referral: counsel the person to seek urgent help for any new headache, jaw or visual symptoms; refer for atypical features, an inadequate or atypical steroid response, difficulty reducing steroids, or suspected giant cell arteritis, which needs same-day rheumatology or ophthalmology assessment. Review symptoms, inflammatory markers, and steroid side effects regularly.' },

  { id:'cks-shoulder', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'💪', dur:'5 min', title:'Shoulder pain', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for shoulder pain. The common causes are rotator cuff disorders including subacromial impingement and cuff tears, adhesive capsulitis or frozen shoulder, glenohumeral and acromioclavicular osteoarthritis, and pain referred from the neck. In lay terms, explain which structure is likely responsible — for example that the rotator cuff is the sleeve of tendons that lifts the arm and can get pinched or worn, or that a frozen shoulder is a process where the capsule tightens and then, importantly, gradually thaws and recovers, though it can be slow. Risk factors include increasing age, repetitive overhead activity, diabetes which strongly predisposes to frozen shoulder, and previous injury. Assessment: ask about onset and any trauma, the site and radiation of pain, a painful arc on elevation, night pain, stiffness, and weakness. Examine the neck to exclude referred pain, inspect for muscle wasting, and assess active and passive range of movement — in a frozen shoulder both are restricted, especially external rotation, whereas in a cuff problem passive movement is often preserved — with specific tests for the rotator cuff and impingement. Red flags: screen for features suggesting other pathology — a history of cancer, a mass, signs of infection such as a hot swollen joint and fever, trauma suggesting a fracture or dislocation, or unexplained significant weakness suggesting a large cuff tear or a neurological cause. Investigations are usually not needed initially; consider an X-ray for trauma, suspected arthritis, or calcific tendinopathy, and ultrasound or specialist imaging for suspected cuff tears. Non-drug management is the mainstay: advise relative rest and activity modification, and offer physiotherapy with a graded exercise and rehabilitation programme for rotator cuff disorders and frozen shoulder, which is core treatment; set realistic expectations, especially that frozen shoulder is self-limiting but often takes one to three years. Drug management: offer analgesia with an NSAID for pain; a subacromial or glenohumeral corticosteroid injection can reduce pain and help engagement with rehabilitation, particularly in impingement or frozen shoulder. Safety-netting and referral: refer for suspected large or full-thickness cuff tears — especially acute traumatic tears in younger people for early repair — instability, suspected septic arthritis urgently, persistent symptoms despite conservative treatment, or diagnostic uncertainty. Review the response to treatment and adjust the plan accordingly.' },

  { id:'cks-osteoporosis', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'🦴', dur:'5 min', title:'Osteoporosis & fragility fracture', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for osteoporosis and fragility fracture risk. Definition: reduced bone strength that predisposes to fractures from low-energy trauma, such as a fall from standing height. In lay language, explain that the bones have become less dense and more fragile, often silently, and that the goal is to strengthen the bones and reduce the chance of a break — particularly of the hip, spine, and wrist — through lifestyle, ensuring enough calcium and vitamin D, and, where the risk is high, a bone-protecting medicine. Risk factors include increasing age, female sex and early menopause, a previous fragility fracture, a parental hip fracture, long-term oral corticosteroids, low body weight, smoking, excess alcohol, and conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis and coeliac disease. Assessment: identify those needing fracture-risk assessment — for example women over 65 and men over 75, and younger people with risk factors. Assess ten-year fracture risk with QFracture or FRAX. Arrange a DXA scan to measure bone mineral density where it will guide management, and feed the result back into FRAX where the tool allows. Investigate to exclude secondary causes and contributors with blood tests — calcium, vitamin D, renal and liver function, thyroid function, and others as indicated. Always assess for existing fragility fractures, including vertebral fractures, which can be silent and present only as height loss or back pain. Non-drug management is for everyone and should be emphasised: weight-bearing and muscle-strengthening exercise, stopping smoking, reducing alcohol, and a structured falls-prevention assessment including review of sedating drugs and vision; ensure adequate dietary calcium and vitamin D, supplementing where intake or levels are low. Drug management for those at high risk and most people after a fragility fracture: first-line is an oral bisphosphonate, alendronate or risedronate, taken correctly on an empty stomach while sitting or standing upright to reduce oesophageal side effects; check dental health and renal function before starting. Intravenous zoledronate or denosumab are alternatives where oral bisphosphonates are unsuitable. Review oral bisphosphonate treatment after about five years, or zoledronate after three, with a drug-holiday decision based on ongoing risk; importantly, do not stop denosumab without specialist advice, because of a rebound increase in fracture risk. Safety-netting and referral: ensure any fragility fracture triggers assessment and treatment, refer for very high risk, treatment failure, or complex secondary causes for consideration of specialist agents, and review adherence and risk over time.' },

  { id:'cks-plantar', cat:'Musculoskeletal', ic:'🦶', dur:'5 min', title:'Plantar heel pain', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for plantar heel pain, most often plantar fasciitis. Definition: pain at the insertion of the plantar fascia on the heel bone, arising from overload and degenerative change rather than true inflammation. In lay terms, explain that the plantar fascia is a strong band supporting the arch of the foot, that it has become overloaded and irritated where it attaches to the heel, and that although it can be slow to settle, it almost always gets better with stretching, supportive footwear, and time. Risk factors include recent increases in walking, running, or standing, unsupportive footwear, obesity, a tight calf or Achilles, and occupations involving prolonged standing. Assessment: the characteristic history is sharp pain under the heel that is worst with the first few steps in the morning or after rest, eases with initial activity, then returns after prolonged standing or walking. Ask about footwear, occupation, recent activity changes, and weight. Examine for localised tenderness at the medial calcaneal tuberosity, worsened by dorsiflexing the toes, and assess foot biomechanics and the Achilles. Red flags and differentials to consider: a calcaneal stress fracture suggested by a recent surge in loading and tenderness on squeezing the heel; fat-pad atrophy; nerve entrapment such as tarsal tunnel syndrome; and an inflammatory cause such as a spondyloarthritis if there is bilateral heel pain in a younger person or other joint or systemic features. Investigations are usually unnecessary; reserve imaging for diagnostic doubt or suspected stress fracture or inflammatory disease. Non-drug management is the mainstay: explain the usually self-limiting but often months-long course to set realistic expectations; advise relative rest from aggravating activities, supportive cushioned footwear with a slightly raised heel, and a structured programme of calf and plantar-fascia stretching exercises, which is the core treatment; gel heel pads or simple orthoses help, and address weight where relevant. Drug management is adjunctive: offer simple analgesia or a topical NSAID for symptom relief. Safety-netting and referral: refer to physiotherapy if not improving with initial measures; for persistent, refractory symptoms, specialist options include a corticosteroid injection — used cautiously because of the risks of fat-pad atrophy and fascia rupture — extracorporeal shockwave therapy, or further assessment. Review progress and reconsider the diagnosis if the pain does not settle as expected.' },

]);
